state and non-state actors; transient, multinational populations; immaterial and affective forms of labor and consumption; superlative and iconic architecture; and economies devoted to such leisure activities as shopping, gambling, and spectacle. These locales are not only popular destinations for migrant workers and mobile tourists from around the globe, but also serve as cultural laboratories for testing new formats and protocols of an emergent post-Fordist form-of-life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTourismxSocial aspectsxChinaxMacau. 0aTourismxSocial aspectsxSoutheast Asia. 0aTourismxSocial aspectsxUnited Arab EmiratesxChinaxMacauxSoutheast AsiaxUnited Arab Emirates. 0aTourismxSocial aspectszChinazMacau. 0aTourismxSocial aspectszSoutheast Asia. 0aTourismxSocial aspectszUnited Arab Emirates. 0aTourismxSocial aspects. 4aAsian Studies. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  atourism, mobility, enclave, space of exception.1 aEasterling, Keller, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElsheshtawy, Yasser, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoh, Daniel P.S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodges, Benjamin Kidder, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLampton, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNdalianis, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNyíri, Pál, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimpson, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimpson, Timothy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWerry, Margaret, econtributor.